# FIVE DOLLAR SEQUENCE BEGIN



>**_SUPER: FIVE DOLLARS_**<



CAROLE SUE (PRELAP)
I’m sorry, Mitch. I just can’t.

INT. NASHVILLE TRIBUNE - FINANCE DEPT - DAY

The words **PETTY CASH**, etched in lucite, float above the head of CAROLE SUE NESTOR (50’s, wears polyester in colors not found in nature). 

MITCH
I used my last five bucks on film for the Jimmy Chin story, Carole Sue.

A half-empty carton of Chesterfield Kings™ sits beside a full ash tray. Carole Sue takes a deep drag and exhales.

CAROLE SUE
You gotta get your film from procurement--You know that. I can’t reimburse for drug store prices. The way they’re cracking down on expenses these days? Lordy, That’s almost twice what we pay wholesale. They would skin me alive.

Small holes in a plexiglass teller window allow sound (and smoke) through. 

MITCH
It’s five dollars. Why they being so tight with money?

CAROLE SUE
Felix’s sisters want to sell the paper, So Felix is trying to make it too profitable to sell.

MITCH
I’m going to have to go home and tell my poor uncle that there’s nothing for us to eat tonight because the paper needs to be profitable.

CAROLE SUE
You can sell that horse hockey  somewhere else, Mitchell Sawyer, cause I ain’t buyin’ it. You should have gotten some film from procurement on Friday.

MITCH
I didn’t even know I’d be working this weekend. Can’t you just help me out this one time?

Mitch places the reimbursement request on the counter and slides it under the small gap in the plexiglass.

CAROLE SUE
Tell you what I can do: Write me a check for twenty-five dollars and I got Sunday and Monday off. I’ll put it in Tuesday evening’s deposit. When you get your paycheck on Tuesday, you take it straight to the bank and you’ll beat the check by a day. I’ll send this up to Felix’s office and if they decide to let it slide, It’ll be in your paycheck next week.

Mitch takes out his checkbook, pen and writes.

MITCH
Awwww... Thanks, Carole Sue.

She slides a torn coupon through the gap.

CAROLE SUE
Here’s a coupon for a value bucket at Mrs Winners. It’ll get you eight pieces and two sides for seven ninety-nine. And you tell that uncle of yours to lay off the bottle--
(Another deep drag from her Chesterfield King™ unfiltered)
--It ain’t good for your liver.

MITCH
As if anyone could tell him anything.

CAROLE SUE
Police got any leads on who killed Jimmy?

Mitch tears off, then slips her the check.

MITCH
Maybe I should be asking you. There are agents at the CIA who don’t have the inside information you do.

CAROLE SUE
(confidentially)
Speaking of, I heard that the Overtons got themselves a spy right here at the trib. 

MITCH
Waatttt??? For real?

CAROLE SUE
My boss’s boss got an unexpected expense request for something called “Computer Forensics”. They’re goin through everyone’s old electronic files and messages. 

MITCH
Wow. That’s big time. The police don’t have the slightest idea who killed jimmy.

Mitch takes the coupon and turns to leave.

CAROLE SUE
Yeah, that sounds about right. Hey, if you tell them their catchphrase they’ll throw in the peach cobbler. Tell them “I’m a winner with Mrs. Winners”. Do you need to write that down?

EST. EAST NASHVILLE NEIGHBORHOOD - TWILIGHT

Mitch parks the VINTAGE VW BUG in the driveway of an urban craftsman-style home. 

EXT. EAST NASHVILLE NEIGHBORHOOD - TWILIGHT

Across the street, a NEIGHBOR is collecting lawn ornaments. NEIGHBOR places a garden gnome **JUST SO**.

NEIGHBOR 
(YELLING and pointing)
I got a new one that looks like Danny DeVito.

Mitch smiles politely and waves, camera bag and white takeaway sack in tow.

INT. HOUSE - TWILIGHT

UNCLE ROSS sleeps upright in his skivvies sitting in a padded reclining chair as the TV shows college football. Open CANS OF MILLER HIGH LIFE litter the coffee table.

Dentures sit in a glass beside an open bottle of scotch on a side table and a one-compartment-per-day plastic pill holder.

Mitch sets down a takeaway bag and picks up the pill holder opening “SATURDAY”. 

Mitch shakes a few of the beer cans from the coffee table and finds one that isn't completely empty.

MITCH
Uncle Ross... Uncle Ross... wake up. Here you need to take this.

Ross takes the pill, swallows and chases it with a sip from the can, belching loudly after he drinks the rest.

MITCH
Why don't you come into the kitchen and have a seat. I'll get you some dinner.

UNCLE ROSS
Your cooking sucks.

MITCH
Which is why I got fried chicken from Mrs. Winners.

UNCLE ROSS
If you didn't get the peach cobbler, I'm kicking your freeloading ass out of my house and disowning you.

MITCH
If I'd known that's all it took, I'd of done it years ago.

.IN THE KITCHEN - CONTINUOUS

Mitch pushes aside dirty plates on the kitchen table, sets down the bag and then looks around in the cluttered kitchen. 

MITCH
(To nobody)
Is indentured servitude really worth a free place to live?

UNCLE ROSS
(walking in)
Stuff it up your apron and bake it, Donna Reed. Ain’t nobody asking you to clean anything.

Mitch sighs and starts cleaning anyway.

.IN THE KITCHEN - LATER

Uncle Ross, still in his skivvies at the table tosses a picked-clean chicken bone on a plate with a few others.

MITCH
I’ll put the rest of the chicken in the fridge and you can have it for lunch tomorrow.
(then)
You hear about Jimmy Chin Lee?

UNCLE ROSS
Stupid summabitch got himself killed.

Mitch puts the last dish in the drying rack and picks up the remote to a small TV in the corner. 

MITCH
(eye-roll)  
Right, it probably was all his fault that he was **murdered in his sleep**.

Mitch scans the major cable networks. 

A sports program is showing the Jimmy Chin story live: An impromptu questioning of Dolly Parton and Jimmy’s name inset, with a birth/death date.

DOLLY (T.V.)
I called his momma this afternoon and that whole family is just in tatters ...And so am I. He was such a gentle soul. Jimmy was good people.

UNCLE ROSS
Probably drugs. Drugs always get the good ones. Every. Damn. Time.

The TV reporter throws to a new segment--Mitch turns up the volume. Deck Layton appears on-camera with the SPORTSCASTER.

SPORTSCASTER (TV)
Deck Layton is the sports editor with the Nashville Tribune. Deck,. Jimmy Chin was not only good on the field, he was an exceptionally bright student in the classroom. What was it that made Jimmy so special, Deck?

MITCH
(to no-one)
Because he doubled the stadium attendance and slightly-racist bobblehead sales?

DECK (TV)
Nobody could touch his calculations, /Jack. He made split-second decisions on the field.

MITCH ^
(under his breath)
/Speaking of slightly racist...

A cat rubs up against Mitch's leg seeking affection.

DECK (TV)
And his story--I mean, he was a Vietnam war orphan adopted by an all-American family and raised to fear God and respect authority. When their son got the scholarship to Vanderbilt, it was like winning the lottery. His record in his first few years here is legendary. He literally got better with every game he played.

SPORTSCASTER (TV)
What can you tell us about the murder? I know it's been less than twelve hours since they found the body. Has there been any progress?

DECK (TV)
Not really Bob, I don't think the police have much of a clue about why he was killed or who did it.

SPORTSCASTER (TV)
Do they think it could be something random?

DECK (TV)
Well, the house was in disarray, but the police didn't really get any forensics.

MITCH
I didn't tell him about the forensics, Frisk. Look at Deck with his “big boy sources”--just like a real reporter.

The cat "meow"s. UNCLE ROSS is leaning his head on his hand, sleeping while sitting up and snoring loudly.

DECK (TV)
But the one I really have to hand it to is our police reporter Mitch Sawyer. This guy never sleeps. He was on this story this morning before the sun came up. 

MITCH
And you just scooped my front page story on TV.

He flips TV-Deck a bird.

Mitch notices a flashing light on the answer-machine on the wall beside the phone. He presses play: 

TOMMIE (machine)
Jackie is grilling steaks. See you at eight.

EST. TOMMIE’S HOUSE - NIGHT

A BLACK DODGE CHALLENGER sits in front of a ranch-style suburban house. There’s a blue magnetic police light sitting on the roof and the tags are government service.

EXT. TOMMIE'S HOUSE - BACKYARD DECK - NIGHT

Mitch's mom, JACKIE, (50's, southern baptist housewife gothic who's let her hair go a little more dyke-a-licious with age) flips a steak on the grill and it sizzles.

MITCH
Uncle Ross sends his love.

JACKIE
That seems unlikely. He hasn’t been sober enough to feel emotions since Nixon resigned. 

MITCH
It was implied in the grunt he made as I left.

JACKIE
Is the singing helping his aphasia?

The air is thick with a humid haze. Mitch sits at a table on a backyard deck, takes a sip of coffee, steaming in spite of the heat. He’s showered and changed into shorts.

MITCH
I don’t know if it’s helping, but I’m considering booking him some dates in Vegas.

That makes both of them smile.

JACKIE
Did you get the front page?

MITCH
Part of me wants to wait at a news stand until distribution gets there at three AM to find out. Probably. I don’t know. We’ll see.

Mitch watches her and lifts his camera...

.MITCH’S NIKON

- Jackie cooks and tries to ignore him taking a photo, but through Mitch's lens, she's beautiful - SNAP

JACKIE
She’s not... I just want you to know: She honestly does like you.

- A lock of hair falls down in front of her eyes - SNAP

.THE DECK

MITCH
(advancing film)
She’s not what?

JACKIE
Feeding you stories just for me.

MITCH
I heard about Jimmy over police radio, then you called and pushed dinner later, so I just did the math--besides, what makes you think I’m not using her for the stories?

JACKIE
After the thing with your father I just really appreciate how you are with her.

MITCH
(smirk)
Yeah, it's amazing how close-minded middle-aged evangelical men are about their wives dating women.

JACKIE
You know what I mean.

Tommie comes out of the house pulling her wet hair back into a pony tail. JACKIE is taking the food off the grill and serving.

TOMMIE
I gotta say, i'm perfectly fine with you dating women.

Kisses Jackie.

JACKIE
He says he's just using you for the stories.

TOMMIE
He is your son, after all

JACKIE
What's that supposed to mean? 

They all sit.

TOMMIE
I was updating the mayor. Pass the butter.

JACKIE
As one does.

MITCH
Still got nothin?

TOMMIE
How does someone go to college and not know anyone? No roommates, no close friends. I can’t even find out if he had a weed dealer. They always have a weed dealer. You’re practically issued one when you register.

Tommie puts lots of salt and butter on her potato and steak.

MITCH
You know how straight edged those evangelicals can be.
(smiling at his mom)
What I can’t figure out is, all through high school you play and love football and are really, honestly, good at the game. Why do you forgo the NFL draft for an extra year to play college ball?

TOMMIE
All anyone would say is that it had to do with his church. God told him to stay in school another year.

JACKIE
God or his church? Because they are not the same thing.

MITCH
That’s what makes me so curious: Did his church guilt him into staying in college another year?

JACKIE
They’re good at that.

MITCH
Mine guilted me into doing some things I regret.

Mitch looks at Jackie but she doesn’t look up from eating.

MITCH
Hey, I don’t supposed you could get his adoption records, could you?

JACKIE
I don’t know. I’ll ask. 

JACKIE
They keep adoption records locked tighter than Fort Knox. It took us almost two years just to get your birth-mother’s name.

TOMMIE
Maybe saying it was “God” was an image thing. …Something that looked good in a Fellowship of Christian Athletes brochure.

Tommie takes a folded piece of paper out of her pocket and hands it to Mitch.

TOMMIE
Speaking of names, Pay attention to the circled ones.

Jackie doesn’t ask questions.

MITCH
(slipping the paper in his pocket)
Thanks. Isn’t there anything that stands out?

TOMMIE
Despite being a quarterback at a S.E.C. School and a household name, nobody seemed particularly broken up about him being gone.

JACKIE
He was isolated from the culture around him.

MITCH
By his parents or by his church?

MITCH
Or Both.

JACKIE ^
Or both.

TOMMIE
They didn't say much when we made the notification, understandably so. He was adopted. His parents are “your people.”

MITCH
Journalists?

JACKIE
Librarians?

TOMMIE
Baptists.

MITCH
(disappointment)
Oh.

JACKIE ^
(disappointment)
Oh.

TOMMIE
Or methodists or something.

MITCH
Well, which is it? Baptists or Methodists?

TOMMIE
Does it matter?

MITCH
Yeah.

JACKIE^
Yeah.

TOMMIE
Well it wasn’t a compound in the hills. Neither church would lead to the kind of isolation necessary to make him choose the church over a million-dollar plus contract.

MITCH
I’d say you’d be surprised some of the crazy things people think God wants them to do, but I know neither of you would be. Did he ever come into the Library?

JACKIE
Not when I was there, but I work days. If you want, we can go see the night girl and see if she knows anything.

MITCH
I’ve got some other leads to follow up first. And then there’s the funeral. 

JACKIE
When is it?

TOMMIE
Tomorrow. In Kentucky.

That sits for a moment in the air, somehow making it more humid.

## FIVE DOLLAR SEQUENCE END

===

